Midterm Airline Analysis

Author

Marvin (Wenxiang) Li

Project Overview - The goal of this project is to analyze airline satisfaction and identify the factors that contribute to it. The dataset used for this analysis is the Airline Satisfaction dataset, which contains information about passengers’ experiences with airlines. This project will involve data cleaning, exploratory data analysis, and machine learning techniques to build a predictive model for airline satisfaction.

def dataset_info(df):
    print("\n--- Shape of Data ---")
    print(f"Rows: {df.shape[0]}, Columns: {df.shape[1]}")
    
    print("\n--- Data Types and Non-Nulls ---")
    print(df.info())

    print("\n--- First 5 Rows ---")
    print(df.head())


# 2. Missing Values 
def missing_values_table(df):
    missing = df.isnull().sum()
    missing_percent = (missing / len(df)) * 100
    missing_table = pd.DataFrame({'Missing Values': missing, 'Percent': missing_percent})
    missing_table = missing_table[missing_table['Missing Values'] > 0]
    missing_table = missing_table.sort_values('Percent', ascending=False)
    
    if missing_table.empty:
        print("\nNo missing values detected.")
    else:
        print("\n--- Missing Values ---")
        print(missing_table)


# 3. Summary Stat
def summary_stats(df):
    print("\n--- Numerical Features ---")
    print(df.describe())

    print("\n--- Categorical Features ---")
    print(df.describe(include=['object']))


# 4. Duplicate Check 
def check_duplicates(df):
    duplicates = df.duplicated().sum()
    print(f"\n--- Duplicates ---\nDuplicate Rows: {duplicates}")


#  5. Univariate Plots 
import math

def univariate_plots(df):
    numeric_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns
    categorical_cols = df.select_dtypes(include='object').columns

    # Plot numeric distributions (2 per row)
    print("\n--- Numeric Distributions ---")
    n = len(numeric_cols)
    rows = math.ceil(n / 2)

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, 2, figsize=(12, 3 * rows))
    axes = axes.flatten()

    for i, col in enumerate(numeric_cols):
        sns.histplot(df[col].dropna(), kde=True, ax=axes[i])
        axes[i].set_title(f'Distribution of {col}')

    # Hide empty subplots
    for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
        fig.delaxes(axes[j])

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    # Plot categorical counts (2 per row)
    print("\n--- Categorical Counts ---")
    n = len(categorical_cols)
    rows = math.ceil(n / 2)

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, 2, figsize=(12, 3 * rows))
    axes = axes.flatten()

    for i, col in enumerate(categorical_cols):
        df[col].value_counts().plot(kind='bar', ax=axes[i])
        axes[i].set_title(f'Counts of {col}')

    for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
        fig.delaxes(axes[j])

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()



# 6. heatmap
def correlation_heatmap(df):
    numeric_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=np.number)
    if numeric_cols.shape[1] > 1:
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
        sns.heatmap(numeric_cols.corr(), annot=True, fmt='.2f', cmap='coolwarm')
        plt.title('Correlation Heatmap')
        plt.show()
    else:
        print("\nNot enough numeric columns for correlation heatmap.")


# run everything
def run_eda(df):
    dataset_info(df)
    missing_values_table(df)
    summary_stats(df)
    check_duplicates(df)
    univariate_plots(df)
    #correlation_heatmap(df)

    print("\nEDA Complete!")

EDA Complete!

Initial EDA: - The dataset has 129880 rows and 25 columns. Data types are mixed, with 20 int64 and 5 object types.
- There are 393 missing values in column ‘Arrival Delay in Minutes’.
- No duplicate.
- The ‘flight distance’ variable is skewed to the right. Most of the flights are less than 2000 miles, with a few outliers exceeding 5000 miles.
- The ‘customer type’ variable is imbalanced, with 90% of customers being loyal and 10% being disloyal.
- The target variable ‘satisfaction’ consits of 73452 neutral (56%) and dissatisfied and 56428 (44% )satisfied. Mildly imbalanced.
- Among all numerical variables, there are continuous variables, such as ‘flight distance’, and ordinal variables, such as ‘inflight wifi service’. This scale difference may affect models that are sensitive to feature magnitude (e.g., Logistic Regression, KNN, or Neural Networks). Feature scaling (e.g., standardization) or transformation may be considered during preprocessing to prevent certain variables from dominating due to their range.

Solution for missing values:
- Impute with the median of the ‘Arrival Delay in Minutes’ column.
- Create a new column ‘Missing Arrival Delay’ to indicate whether the value is missing or not. This will help capture any potential patterns related to missing values.

Code 
data_full['Missing Arrival Delay'] = data_full['Arrival Delay in Minutes'].isnull().astype(int)
median_delay = data_full['Arrival Delay in Minutes'].median()
data_full['Arrival Delay in Minutes'] = data_full['Arrival Delay in Minutes'].fillna(median_delay)

        ]
Code 
# Standardized pipeline (for scale-sensitive models)
preprocessor_std = ColumnTransformer(transformers=[
    ('num', StandardScaler(), num_cols),
    ('cat', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore', drop='first'), cat_cols),
    ('ord', StandardScaler(), ordinal_cols)
])

# Raw pipeline (for tree-based models)
preprocessor_raw = ColumnTransformer(transformers=[
        ('num', 'passthrough', num_cols),
        ('cat', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore', drop='first'), cat_cols),
        ('pass', 'passthrough', ordinal_cols)
])

4. Modeling

a. Random Forest Classifier
Code 
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import (
    recall_score,
    precision_score,
    f1_score,
    confusion_matrix,
    ConfusionMatrixDisplay,
    classification_report
)
Code 
pipeline_rf = Pipeline([
    ('preprocessor', preprocessor_raw),
    ('classifier', RandomForestClassifier(
        random_state=42, 
        n_jobs=-1
    ))
])

param_grid_rf = {
    'classifier__n_estimators': [100],
    'classifier__max_depth': [5,10],
    'classifier__min_samples_leaf': [1, 2]
}

# Lighter grid search
grid_search_rf = GridSearchCV(
    pipeline_rf,
    param_grid_rf,
    cv=3,
    scoring='f1',
    n_jobs=-1,
    verbose=1
)

grid_search_rf.fit(X_train, y_train)

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.ensemble import StackingClassifier
from xgboost import XGBClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_validate
Code 
def get_stacking():
    level0 = [
        ('lr', LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, random_state=42)),
        ('xgb', XGBClassifier(eval_metric='logloss', random_state=42))
    ]
    level1 = LogisticRegression()

    stacking_model = StackingClassifier(
        estimators=level0,
        final_estimator=level1,
        cv=5,
        n_jobs=-1
    )
    return stacking_model
Code 
def get_models(preprocessor):
    models = {
        'Logistic Regression': make_pipeline(preprocessor, LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, random_state=42)),
        'XGBoost': make_pipeline(preprocessor, XGBClassifier(eval_metric='logloss', random_state=42)),
        'Stacking' : make_pipeline(preprocessor, get_stacking()),
    }
    return models
Code 
def evaluate_model(model, X, y):
    cv = KFold(n_splits=3, shuffle=True, random_state=42)
    scoring = ['accuracy', 'f1', 'precision', 'recall']
    cv_results = cross_validate(model, X, y, cv=cv, scoring=scoring, n_jobs=-1, return_train_score=False)
    return {
        'accuracy': cv_results['test_accuracy'],
        'f1': cv_results['test_f1'],
        'precision': cv_results['test_precision'],
        'recall': cv_results['test_recall']
    }
Code 
def compare_models(X_train, y_train, preprocessor):
    models = get_models(preprocessor)
    metrics = ['accuracy', 'precision', 'recall', 'f1']
    results = {metric: [] for metric in metrics}
    names = []

    for name, model in models.items():
        print(f"Evaluating: {name}")
        scores = evaluate_model(model, X_train, y_train)  # assumes evaluate_model returns means only

        names.append(name)
        for metric in metrics:
            results[metric].append(scores[metric].mean())

        print(f">{name:<18} | "
              f"Accuracy: {scores['accuracy'].mean():.3f} | "
              f"Precision: {scores['precision'].mean():.3f} | "
              f"Recall: {scores['recall'].mean():.3f} | "
              f"F1: {scores['f1'].mean():.3f}")

    # Create summary DataFrame
    summary_df = pd.DataFrame(results, index=names)
    print("\nModel Comparison Summary:")
    print(summary_df.round(3).sort_values('f1', ascending=False))

    # Bar plot for F1 scores
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
    plt.barh(summary_df.index, summary_df['f1'], color='skyblue')
    plt.xlabel("F1 Score")
    plt.title("Model Comparison (F1 Score)")
    plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
    plt.show()

5. Conclusion

  • Across all three models, the dominant drivers of passenger satisfaction consistently center around:

  • Service convenience (online boarding, booking ease)

  • Operational factors (baggage handling, gate location)

  • Service experience (on-board and inflight service)

  • The models show remarkably consistent performance, with precision and recall both exceeding 0.93 across classes. This indicates that the dataset contains strong and reliable signals, and that different modeling approaches—ensemble methods or neural networks—can each effectively capture and leverage them.

  • Potential improvement for this survey would be to reduce missing values in ‘Arrival Delay in Minutes’ column.

  • From a business perspective, at least based on this dataset, this analysis shows that:

    • The majority of passengers of this survey are loyal customers.
    • Loyalty customers mostly travel for business trips.
    • They are more concerned about convenience and operational factors than service experience.
    • They are less concerened about add-on services such as inflight wifi, food, and entertainment.
